<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-968-926  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 968 926.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Jan 16 1989 v6 n2 p19(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Research unmasks broadband issues: group examines broadband ISDNnetworks, readies general public policy recommendations. (Centerfor Telecommunications and Information Studies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eckerson, Wayne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A study by the Center for Telecommunications and InformationStudies (CTIS) at Columbia University shows that the debate overthe future implementation of integrated broadband networks isdividing experts into two camps.andP;  Purists believe that integratedbroadband networks, or broadband ISDN, should consist ofall-fiber, all-digital circuits that are connected directly to thehome or business.andP;  Pragmatists believe that the expense ofconnecting fiber circuits directly to the home or business willinhibit the growth of the networks.andP;  They favor the use ofnarrowband transmission over copper wire and coaxial cable inaddition to fiber cables.andP;  Integrated broadband networks transmitvoice, data and video over a single digital fiber-optic circuitand can provide the full range of services available from thepublic telephone network in addition to cable television andseveral new services.andP;  CTIS's history is also discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BroadbandStudyISDNImplementationNarrowbandNetworksColumbia University. Center for Telecommunications and InformationStudiesTelephone Companies.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Research under way at Columbia University. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>